				 Three-year JSW Steel investment blitz
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Jindal: Big plans																								Chennai, Nov. 26: JSW Steel has lined up an investment of Rs 40,000 crore over the next three years, including doubling the capacity of a plant in Tamil Nadu. 																								Sajjan Jindal, vice-chairman and managing director of the JSW group, which is part of the $6-billion .P. Jindal group, said the entire group planned to invest Rs 80,000 crore in the next three years. Half of that capital expenditure will come from the JSW group.																								The JSW group will pump Rs 20,000 crore in its core steel business, Jindal said shortly before meeting Tamil Nadu chief minister M Karunanidhi to discuss the progress of his companys projects in the state. 																								Another Rs 12,000 crore will be invested in the power sector, and the balance Rs 8,000 crore in cement, aluminium units and port development in other parts of the country.																								Of the total amount, Rs 25,000 crore will be funded through debts and the rest from internal accruals, he added. JSW Steel plans to invest Rs 7,500 crore in Tamil Nadu over the next three years for capacity expansion and setting up mining facilities.																								Jindal told reporters here that subsidiary Siscol planned to use iron ore available in Kanchamalai area in Salem and in Tiruvannamalai district by putting up mining facilities and benefication plants at an investment of Rs 400 crore. This will generate direct and indirect employment for over 3,000 people.																								It also plans to increase capacity at its existing plant in Salem from one million tonnes to two million tonnes per annum at Rs 3,000 crore, he said. The group also wants to set up a thermal power station with a capacity of 1,000mw, which could be expanded to 2,000mw for Rs 4,000 crore. The group has identified Ennore port as the ideal site for the project, he said.
